 Monmouthshire, Wales":"Raglan, Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Leeds, Yorkshire, England":"Leeds, Jórvík, England, United Kingdom","Usk, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Usk, Monmouthshire, Wales"},"nl":{"1329–13 August 1363":"1329–13 augustus 1363","1329–1363":"1329–1363","1332–1372":"1332–1372","1330–Female":"1330–Overleden","1355–1410":"1355–1410","1309–1361":"1309–1361","1300–1348":"1300–1348","1330":"1330","1363":"1363","1361":"1361","1372":"1372","Abt 1349":"circa 1349","1348":"1348","13 August 1363":"13 augustus 1363","1337":"1337","1355":"1355","1300":"1300","1410":"1410","1453":"1453","1332":"1332","1309":"1309","1329":"1329","England":"England","Fryston, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Raglan, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Raglan, Monmouthshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Leeds, Yorkshire, England":"Leeds, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Usk, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Usk, Monmouthshire, Wales"},"en":{"1329–13 August 1363":"1329–13 August 1363","1329–1363":"1329–1363","1332–1372":"1332–1372","1330–Female":"1330–Deceased","1355–1410":"1355–1410","1309–1361":"1309–1361","1300–1348":"1300–1348","1330":"1330","1363":"1363","1361":"1361","1372":"1372","Abt 1349":"about 1349","1348":"1348","13 August 1363":"13 August 1363","1337":"1337","1355":"1355","1300":"1300","1410":"1410","1453":"1453","1332":"1332","1309":"1309","1329":"1329","England":"England","Fryston, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Raglan, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Raglan, Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Leeds, Yorkshire, England":"Leeds, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Usk, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Usk, Monmouthshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Rawson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: patronymic meaning ‘son of <i>Rauf</i> or <i>Rau</i>’, Middle English forms of   Ralph   (see   Rawe   3)."],"variants":[{"name":"Ralph","meanings":["English: from Anglo-Norman and Middle English <i>Raulf</i>, <i>Ralf</i>, an Old French form of ancient Germanic <i>Radulf</i> (from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel, advice’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’), hence the usual latinization of the name as <i>Radulfus</i>. <i>Ralph</i> was a common personal name among the Normans and from the mid 13th century among the native English. Almost 7% of men in the late 14th century were named <i>Ralph</i>. It was pronounced in a variety of ways, giving rise to a large number of different surnames. <i>Ralf</i> could be shortened to <i>Raff</i>, hence the surname   Raff   and possibly   Raffel  . <i>Raulf</i> was sometimes shortened to <i>Raul</i>, giving us   Rall   and <b>Rawlin</b> (see   Rawling  ). It also appears as <i>Rauf</i>, which was often shortened to <i>Rau</i>, hence the surnames   Rawe   and <b>Rawkin</b> (‘young Ralph’), as well as   Haw  ,   Hawkins  ,   Daw   and   Dawkins  , derived from rhyming pet forms. In late Middle English the diphthong <i>-au-</i> was sometimes simplified to long <i>-a-</i>, later pronounced ‘ay’ as in modern English <i>day</i>, which accounts for <b>Rafe</b>. This pronunciation of the personal name <i>Ralph</i> is still occasionally found in modern times. <i>Ralph</i> is a learned spelling of <i>Ralf</i> that became common in the 16th century. In Anglo-Norman and Middle English usage, the rarer personal name <i>Rolf</i> was sometimes confused with <i>Ralf</i>, which explains why <i>Ralf</i> is an alternative source for   Rolf  ,   Rowe  ,   Dow  , and their derivatives."]},{"name":"Rowson","meanings":["English: variant of   Rawson  . Compare   Dawson   and   Dowson  ."]}]},{"name":"Ralph","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ralf","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":8,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Lord Ralph Rawson II was born in 1329, in England, his father, Ralph de Blewett, was 20 and his mother, Elizabeth Verch Rhys, was 29. He married Ann about 1349, in Leeds, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 13 August 1363, in his hometown, at the age of 34."},"et":{"1329–13 August 1363":"1329–13. august 1363","1329–1363":"1329–1363","1332–1372":"1332–1372","1330–Female":"1330–Surnud","1355–1410":"1355–1410","1309–1361":"1309–1361","1300–1348":"1300–1348","1330":"1330","1363":"1363","1361":"1361","1372":"1372","Abt 1349":"umbes 1349","1348":"1348","13 August 1363":"13. august 1363","1337":"1337","1355":"1355","1300":"1300","1410":"1410","1453":"1453","1332":"1332","1309":"1309","1329":"1329","England":"England","Fryston, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Raglan, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Raglan, Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Leeds, Yorkshire, England":"Leeds, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Usk, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Usk, Monmouthshire, Wales"},"fi":{"1329–13 August 1363":"1329–13. elokuuta 1363","1329–1363":"1329–1363","1332–1372":"1332–1372","1330–Female":"1330–Kuollut","1355–1410":"1355–1410","1309–1361":"1309–1361","1300–1348":"1300–1348","1330":"1330","1363":"1363","1361":"1361","1372":"1372","Abt 1349":"noin 1349","1348":"1348","13 August 1363":"13. elokuuta 1363","1337":"1337","1355":"1355","1300":"1300","1410":"1410"